snippet.title: YouTube Creators for Change: Omar Hussein
snippet.description:
Omar Hussein is a creator who found his voice on YouTube. Omar created "Al-Tayer" a social satire show focused on the Saudi environment surrounding him. As his show gained popularity, Omar became the CEO of Uturn Entertainment, a leading multi-channel network in Saudi Arabia. As his channel neared a million subscribers, Omar stopped broadcasting his show and focused on earning a master’s degree in the UK. Omar has diversified his interest in YouTube by creating a new, self-titled vlogging channel which has become his primary home on the site.

For his YouTube Creators for Change project, Omar aims to promote empathy and understanding towards the Muslim community through a music video that demonstrates the importance of education as a way to generate tolerance and acceptance for everyone.

To see Omar's Creators for Change project, visit his channel -- https://www.youtube.com/user/honga1st

snippet.title: YouTube Creators for Change: Franchesca Ramsey
snippet.description:
Franchesca Ramsey is a YouTube vlogger and writer known for her unique voice, social commentary and comedy. In 2016, Franchesca was one of four YouTube creators who asked live video questions of the US presidential candidates at the Democratic debates in Charleston, South Carolina. In addition to making YouTube videos, she's a former writer and correspondent for Comedy Central's ""The Nightly Show with Larry Wilmore"" and is currently the host of MTV's ""Decoded"".

For her YouTube Creators for Change project, Franchesca discusses policing in America today and presents some impactful ways to use your voice in your local community.

To see Franchesca's Creators for Change project, visit her channel -- https://www.youtube.com/user/chescaleigh

snippet.title: YouTube Creators for Change: Dina Tokio
snippet.description:
London-based blogger and recent mom Dina Tokio has a keen eye for fashion and all things beauty related. She creates content for her YouTube channel and blog that ranges from styling tips to everyday lifestyle vlogs and passionate rants. Dina was part of YouTube's #MadeForYou campaign, where she was selected as one the UK's most influential social media stars of the moment!

For her YouTube Creators for Change project, Dina has created a four-part series that aims to celebrate Muslim women who have shunned cultural stereotypes in hopes of inspiring young girls that they can go on to do whatever it is they want in life with or without a hijab.


To see Dina's Creators for Change project, visit her channel -- https://www.youtube.com/user/dinatokio

snippet.title: YouTube Creators for Change: Natalie Tran
snippet.description:
Since uploading her first video on YouTube in 2006, Natalie Tran’s YouTube channel has grown a global fanbase of over 1.8 million subscribers with over half a billion channel views. Tran's videos are a collection of scripted comedy clips that contain a mixture of monologues and sketches focusing on the oddities of awkward everyday situations – with Tran playing multiple characters.

For her YouTube Creators for Change project, Natalie created a short series of videos from her very personal experiences that tackle some of the racism and sexism people in interracial relationships face in hopes of generating understanding and empathy.

To see Natalie's Creators for Change project, visit her channel -- https://www.youtube.com/user/communitychannel

snippet.title: YouTube Creators for Change: Barış Özcan
snippet.description:
Istanbul-based storyteller Baris produces and broadcasts YouTube videos about art, design, technology and literature. Every week, Baris tries to tell simple stories around complex technological concepts and social issues. Baris is an award-winning art director at Abak.us – the creative agency he founded – and a prominent public speaker at events like TEDx in Turkey. He is married to one of the first-ever Turkish internet bloggers, Devletsah, and has a son.

For his YouTube Creators for Change project, Baris produced a six-part YouTube series in scripted/fiction format on topics related to hate, race, religion, sexual orientation, extremism and xenophobia. Each webisode will bring us into the world of a detective furiously working solve to a mystery and show us his experiences with some of the darkest corners of human nature.

To see Baris' Creators for Change project, visit his channel channel -- https://www.youtube.com/user/b31416

snippet.title: YouTube Creators for Change: Abdel En Vrai
snippet.description:
Abdel discovered his passion for making people laugh through stand-up comedy. He started his YouTube channel, Abdel en Vrai, 3 years ago and uses it to share content about peace, love and tolerance. Humor helps get the message across with more impact. Abdel has always been an activist for equality and social justice, which led him to win the Brussels Citizen of the Year Award in 2013.

For his YouTube Creators for Change project, Abdel hosted two workshop-style events focused on engaging Belgian youth with content creation. Additionally, he will be releasing a series of videos to further his message about Muslim tolerance and acceptance.

To view Abdel's Creators for Change project, visit his channel -- https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCfQKQmVsZVslQsVhK_eR-mw

snippet.title: YouTube Creators for Change: AIB
snippet.description:
All India Bakchod (AIB) is one of India's funniest and edgiest comedy collectives. Consisting of comedians Rohan Joshi, Tanmay Bhat, Gursimran Khamba and Ashish Shakya, AIB has revolutionized comedy content in India. They started with India’s first ever, and most heard, comedy podcast, then went on to become one of the biggest YouTube channels in India with over 1.7 million subscribers. In 2015, they did the first ever news comedy show "On Air With AIB" which was seen on digital as well as prime time television. AIB belongs to an emerging group of digital crusaders advocating for the cause of net neutrality in India.

For their YouTube Creators for Change project, they use comedic parody to highlight the harassment, misogyny and hatred women face online every day and create a conversation around how to make digital environments safer.

To see AIB's Creators for Change project, visit their channel: https://www.youtube.com/user/allindiabakchod

snippet.title: YouTube Creators for Change: Cameo Project
snippet.description:
Cameo Project is a YouTube channel based in Indonesia. They are known for their fun, lively videos in which they talk about social issues and sensitive topics in Indonesia in order to raise awareness among the Indonesian people. In addition to videos centered around politics and social issues, they make funny, relatable videos about life in Indonesia.

For their YouTube Creators for Change project, Cameo partnered with an NGO called ""Maarif Institute"" who has a wide network of students across the country. Together they aim to educate high school and university students in 10 cities in Indonesia about the importance of creating positive content.

To see Cameo Project's Creator for Change project, visit their channel -- https://www.youtube.com/user/CameoProject

snippet.title: #ProudToBe: Celebrate Brave Voices this Pride
snippet.description:
In a world where some people still try to silence LGBTQ+ voices, the act of being yourself is an act of bravery for all to see. And in the context of a global climate that highlights the vulnerability of LGBTQ+ rights, it’s more important than ever that LGBTQ+ voices and stories are shared and heard. 

An inclusive, vibrant, ever-expanding LGBTQ+ community has been a vital part of YouTube since we started. And we’re proud to stand with a group that believes every human being deserves the right to be who they are and love who they love. So to all those brave voices who continue to make Youtube the colorful, diverse and supportive place it is, we’re #ProudToBe with you.

--

YouTube Creators for Change is proud to launch #ProudToBe, our fifth annual Pride campaign. Creators for Change is YouTube’s global initiative dedicated to amplifying the voices of role models who are tackling difficult social issues with their channels. From combating hate speech, to countering xenophobia and extremism, to simply making the case for greater tolerance and empathy toward others, these creators are helping generate positive social change with their global fan bases. Learn more at https://www.youtube.com/yt/creators-for-change/

snippet.title: YouTube: Our Brand Mission
snippet.description:
Our mission is to give everyone a voice and show them the world.
We believe that everyone deserves to have a voice, and that the world is a better place when we listen, share and build community through our stories. Our values are based on four essential freedoms that define who we are: freedom of expression, freedom of opportunity, freedom of information and the freedom to belong

For more about who we are visit www.youtube.com/yt/about

snippet.title: Register to Vote in 1:34 - #voteIRL

1 minute. 34 seconds. In the U.S., that’s all it takes to register to vote. A single registration lasts a lifetime of elections. We’ve made it easy for you here: http://g.co/elections/134

There are a lot of things you can do in 1:34. You can shoot hoops, enjoy popcorn, do a plank, make tea, or sing a song. It’s probably been about 1:34 since you started reading this description.

We want to make sure that everyone has the ability to use their voice and cast their vote this November. 
But in order to #voteIRL, it’s essential that you are registered before mid October.

snippet.title: #voteIRL - Use Your Voice. Vote in Real Life.
snippet.description:
Today, we’re announcing YouTube’s get out the vote campaign, #voteIRL, where together with the YouTube creator community, we’re helping get young people to the polls. Even though people are clearly following the election online, we want to make sure they get involved “in real life,” too. 

We believe in giving everyone a voice. So this U.S. elections season, we’re committed to making sure that people--especially young people--use their voice by voting.

REGISTER TO VOTE NOW: http://g.co/elections/134

Did you know it only takes 1:34 to register to vote? For National Voter Registration Day, starting today the YouTube community will be making 1:34 videos to make sure that you're registered to vote.

snippet.title: #ProudToBe: Coming Together to Celebrate Identity
snippet.description:
Celebrating the inspiring voices who are #ProudToBe
SHARE THIS VIDEO: https://youtu.be/dtCyepuLt8Q
MUSIC: "Nothing Without Love" by Nate Ruess

From commemorating Pride parades to opening up about transitions and explaining the ABCs of LGBT (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uFqLrSHWNT4), YouTube is a place where anyone can belong no matter who they are or who they love. That is why today we want to help people honor and celebrate who they’re #ProudToBe.

Now, more than ever, it’s important that we help accept, love, and celebrate one another. In the wake of the tragic events in Orlando, we stand together in support of the LGBTQ community. We stand together with everyone who has the courage to own and share their identity. We stand together to show the power of solidarity, the power of love, the power of pride. To those beautiful and brave voices who continue to make YouTube the vibrant, diverse and empathetic community it is, we are #ProudToBe with you.

JOIN IN: Who are you #ProudToBe? 
Upload a video or share a post with #ProudToBe in the title so others can find it.
